<h3>The Question</h3>
<p>
    A recurring real problem: designers bring many visual variations of one core component. Some are
    structural and warrant a new block; many are <em>mostly visual yet not purely CSS-achievable</em> —
    inject an icon, add a status badge, wrap a child in a popover, swap a sub-element. When WE already
    ships a navigation block that meets every a11y requirement (<code>nav-list</code>, the W3C APG
    Disclosure Navigation pattern), rebuilding it per variation is waste. React offers a rich reuse menu
    (replace a sub-component, HOC / decoration, prop-merge, abstract-piece split, context config).
    <strong>What is the HTML-first, standards-based set of strategies WE should offer for the same
    reuse</strong> — and which are first-class vs. left to userland, in a way that preserves the base
    block's a11y guarantees? This survey grounds backlog
    <a href="/backlog/1795-html-first-composition-strategies-for-re-skinning-an-a11y-co/">#1795</a> per
    design-first step&nbsp;1, mapping each React pattern onto a web-platform primitive before the call.
</p>

<h3>Recommendation (prepared in #1795, post-skeptic)</h3>
<ol>
    <li><strong>Three strategies are cleanly first-class &amp; composable</strong> (slots, behavior/decoration,
        abstract-piece-split convention) — none excludes another. <strong>Sub-component replacement</strong>
        is sanctioned but <em>blocked</em>: #854's contract is ratified, but the webregistries runtime is
        mid-port to FUI (#901's graduated file is absent from HEAD; open re-home items incl. #1483/#1545) —
        adopt the ruling, mark the build blocked-on the re-home. <strong>Context-driven configuration is
        not a free-standing visual-variation strategy</strong> — it is the "configure-one-block" branch the
        fork below defaults against, and survives only for non-visual config (locale, data, flags).</li>
    <li><strong>The one genuine fork is where the a11y contract is owned</strong> for mostly-visual variation:
        compose over the a11y-complete base (the base stays one block and owns its a11y contract) vs.
        configure one block to render many visual variants from injected config. The branches compose only at
        the margin — config may <em>select which presentation-only slots appear</em>, never own the contract.
        <strong>Default: compose-over-base</strong>, argued on native-first + a11y-ownership merit; #023
        ("distinct tags, NOT one configurable element") is cited as analogy, not controlling precedent.</li>
    <li><strong>A forced invariant (ratify), but contract-level — not a per-strategy vector:</strong> the
        a11y contract is single-sourced on the base block, and any sanctioned composition strategy must be
        <em>non-destructive</em> to it (it may add to the ARIA/focus surface, never override or remove it).
        Verifying a given composed variant is a FUI/Plateau conformance-run concern, not a WE-shipped proof
        matrix (composed variants are not expressible in the vector schema, and the verifier/impl live
        downstream per the constellation rule).</li>
</ol>

<h3>Finding 1 — the motivating block is real, and so is the a11y gap</h3>
<p>
    The <code>nav-list</code> block is concrete, not hypothetical: "Accessible navigation menus using the
    W3C APG Disclosure Navigation pattern… keyboard navigation, collapsible sections, and router
    integration with aria-current tracking" (<code>we:src/_data/blocks/nav-list.json</code>), composed of
    <code>NavListBehavior</code> (roving tabindex) + <code>NavSectionBehavior</code>
    (<code>aria-expanded</code> disclosure), with a git-tracked conformance demo
    (<code>we:demos/reveal-nav-conformance.html</code>). A11y conformance vectors exist as a corpus
    (<code>we:conformance-vectors/presentation-a11y.vectors.ts</code> asserts aria-live announcement, focus
    management, inert reading-order — judging only the observable platform surface, never impl internals).
    But <strong>no suite proves a <em>composed</em> variant preserves the base's guarantees</strong> — that
    is the enforcement seam the decision must add.
</p>

<h3>Finding 2 — strategy → web-platform primitive (four already in the tree)</h3>
<ul>
    <li><strong>Slots</strong> (inject icon/badge/popover) → shadow <code>&lt;slot&gt;</code>, named and
        default, already the standard authoring form in WE's <code>&lt;component&gt;</code> renderer
        (<code>we:blocks/renderers/component/__fixtures__/component-cases.ts</code>); the JSX directive layer
        maps named child slots to lifecycle states
        (<code>we:blocks/renderers/jsx/directives.ts:74-80</code>). Native, lowest-risk.</li>
    <li><strong>Sub-component replacement</strong> (the CustomLink analog) → <strong>scoped custom element
        registries</strong>, governed by #854 (ratified, codified <code>#component-dc</code>): registries as
        first-class declared elements associated by DOM IDREF, a <code>CustomAttribute</code> binding doing
        the scoped <code>define</code>. Build is unstarted (#900 → #901); no <code>CustomLink</code> exists
        yet — specced-but-greenfield.</li>
    <li><strong>Behavior / decoration</strong> (the HOC analog) → <code>CustomAttribute</code> behaviors —
        the most mature strategy, with real child-decorating examples that mutate a host's a11y state
        (<code>we:blocks/router/behaviors/RouteLinkBehavior.ts</code> sets <code>aria-current="page"</code>
        on its host <code>&lt;a&gt;</code>).</li>
    <li><strong>Context-driven configuration</strong> → <strong>webinjectors</strong> IDREF (declarative
        provider resolution, <code>we:_site/plugs/webinjectors/declarativeInjector.ts</code>) and
        <strong>webexpressions</strong> <code>{% raw %}{{ }}{% endraw %}</code> for object-valued binding
        (<code>we:conformance-vectors/text-node.vectors.ts</code>), layered over the resolved three-layer
        project-config carve (#1780: contract→WE, resolver→FUI, values→product).</li>
    <li><strong>Abstract-piece split</strong> → a <em>convention</em>, not a single mechanism: #023's
        distinct-tags-assemble-trait-sets plus #715's tree-shakable webtraits. Userland authoring discipline
        WE need not ship a primitive for.</li>
</ul>

<h3>Finding 3 — the web platform shipped the hard parts</h3>
<p>
    Two primitives the HTML-first menu leans on are no longer polyfill-only. <strong>Scoped custom element
    registries</strong> — multiple definitions for one tag name, attached to a shadow root via
    <code>attachShadow({ customElementRegistry })</code> — are now default in Chromium&nbsp;146 and shipped
    in Safari (revamped spec at whatwg/html#10854). <strong>Imperative slot assignment</strong>
    (<code>HTMLSlotElement.assign()</code> with <code>slotAssignment: "manual"</code>) lets a block slot
    sub-components by DOM position or id without duplicate <code>slot</code> attributes — the native engine
    for dynamic sub-component slotting. So strategies&nbsp;1 and&nbsp;2 rest on native, interoperable
    primitives, validating the HTML-first stance over a framework-runtime composition layer.
</p>

<h3>Finding 4 — the strategies split three ways, not "all support-all"</h3>
<p>
    The fork-existence test does <em>not</em> classify all five as composable peers. Slots, behavior/decoration,
    and abstract-piece-split are cleanly first-class and compose (slot an icon <em>and</em> decorate a child
    <em>and</em> swap a sub-part on one block). Sub-component replacement is sanctioned but
    <strong>blocked</strong> on the webregistries FUI re-home. Context-driven configuration is the outlier:
    for the decision's <em>visual</em> use-case it is the "configure-one-block" branch the fork defaults
    against — so counting it as a fifth support-all strategy is incoherent with that default. It is sanctioned
    only for <em>non-visual</em> config and otherwise folds into the fork below.
</p>

<h3>Finding 5 — the one genuine fork: where the a11y contract is owned</h3>
<p>
    The mostly-visual variation case forces a real either/or on a11y-contract ownership.
    <strong>(a) Compose-over-base</strong>: the a11y-complete base stays a single block and owns its a11y
    contract; variation arrives by slotting, decorating, scoped-replacing a sub-part, or theme tokens — and
    variation that can't be expressed that way is <em>structural</em>, so it becomes a distinct block.
    <strong>(b) Configure-one-block</strong>: one block exposes a rich injected-config surface and renders
    many visual variants internally, dissolving the single contract into a config matrix. The branches
    compose only at the margin — config may <em>select which presentation-only slots appear</em> over a
    compose-over-base base, never own the contract. <strong>Default (a)</strong>, argued on native-first +
    a11y-ownership merit (one block owning one contract is easier to keep conformant than a config matrix)
    for the block-reskin case directly; #023 ("distinct tags, NOT one configurable element") is droplist-scoped
    and cited here as analogy, not controlling precedent. Context-config stays for behavioral / data wiring,
    not visual restructuring.
</p>

<h3>Finding 6 — overlap is bounded; the decision is non-duplicative</h3>
<p>
    Adjacent composition work does not own this menu: #646 is the devtools <em>assembler</em> that emits
    ejectable recipes (it would <em>consume</em> these strategies); #715 (webtraits) is the
    cross-bundler <em>delivery</em> of trait composition; #748 shipped the block <em>anatomy view</em>
    (inspection, resolved); #023 ruled droplist trait composition (resolved, and the precedent for Finding&nbsp;5).
    The one hard dependency: sub-component replacement is settled by #854 / built by #901 — #1795 adopts that
    ruling rather than re-deciding it.
</p>

